            "content": "# Patterns and conventions\n\n## Error handling\n\nThe codebase uses metadata-rich error classes from `@factory/logging/errors`. Two categories:\n\n- **`MetaError`** for internal/unexpected failures (500s). Carries structured metadata for Sentry.\n- **`ResponseErrorXXX`** classes (400, 401, 403, 404, etc.) for user-facing HTTP errors.\n\nRules:\n- Never throw vanilla `Error`. Always use `MetaError` or the appropriate `ResponseErrorXXX`.\n- Bubble errors by default. Only catch if you have a concrete fallback or need to translate the error.\n- If you call `logException`, handle the error locally (no rethrow). If you rethrow, do not log -- just add breadcrumbs with `logInfo`/`logWarn`.\n- Let middleware format HTTP responses. Throw errors and let `handleRouteMiddleware` convert them to `NextResponse`.\n\n## Logging\n\nImport from `@factory/logging`:\n\n```typescript\nimport { logInfo, logWarn, logException } from '@factory/logging';\n```\n\n- `logInfo(message, metadata?)` -- informational breadcrumbs for debugging\n- `logWarn(message, metadata?)` -- warnings that don't break functionality\n- `logException(error, message, metadata?)` -- full error context with stack traces\n\nNever call `logError` (it doesn't exist in this codebase). Structured metadata is auto-scrubbed for secrets before being sent to Sentry.\n\n## File organization\n\nESLint enforces strict file organization:\n\n- **Enums** must live in `enums.ts` files. `enums.ts` can only contain enum declarations, type aliases, and interfaces.\n- **Types** must live in `types.ts` files.\n- **API types** go in `packages/common/src/api/{service}/types.ts`.\n- Use absolute imports (`@factory/...`, `@/...`). No `require()` -- use ES6 imports only.\n\n## State management (frontend)\n\nRedux Toolkit with entity adapters. Key rules:\n- Select state precisely, not generally. Use individual `useSelector` calls per field.\n- Components should be as stateless as possible. Prefer local state over Redux.\n- Top-level page components can delegate state from Redux, but inner components should receive props.\n\n## UI components\n\nAll UI must use `@factory/core-ui` primitives:\n- Layout: `Box`, `Flex`, `Grid`\n- Forms: `Button`, `Input`, `Dropdown`\n- Typography: `Header`, `Text`\n- Never use raw `<div>`, `<button>`, `<input>` directly\n- Never hardcode colors -- use `colors.semantics` from the design system\n\n## Feature flags\n\nDefined in `packages/common/src/feature-flags/constants.ts` using Statsig:\n\n```typescript\nconst isEnabled = useFeatureFlagValue(FactoryFeatureFlags.NewFeature);\n```\n\nServer-side:\n```typescript\nconst featureFlags = await getFeatureFlagInstance();\nconst isEnabled = await featureFlags.checkFlag(FactoryFeatureFlags.NewFeature, orgId);\n```\n\n## Testing patterns\n\n- Frontend tests need `/** @jest-environment jsdom */` at file top\n- Mock at the top level with `jest.requireActual` to preserve non-mocked exports\n- Use `beforeEach(() => jest.resetAllMocks())` for clean state\n- For singleton modules, use `jest.resetModules()` + dynamic `import()` in each test\n- Colocate test files with source files\n- Test the public API of each module, not internals\n\n## PR conventions\n\nTitle format: `type(scope): description`\n- Types: `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `refactor`, `test`, `chore`\n- Scope: workspace name from `apps/*` or `packages/*`, or `monorepo`\n- Include Linear ticket in the description (e.g., `Closes FAC-1234`)\n",
