            "content": "# Tool execution\n\nTools are the mechanism by which Droid interacts with the development environment. When the LLM determines it needs to read a file, run a command, or make an edit, it emits a tool call that the CLI executes and returns the result.\n\n## Tool lifecycle\n\n```mermaid\ngraph TD\n    LLM[LLM response] -->|contains tool_use| Parse[Parse tool call]\n    Parse --> Permission{User permission?}\n    Permission -->|granted| Execute[Execute tool]\n    Permission -->|denied| Skip[Skip with message]\n    Execute --> Result[Format result]\n    Result --> Return[Return to LLM]\n    Return --> LLM\n```\n\n## Tool architecture\n\nTools are defined in two layers:\n\n1. **Interface definitions** in `packages/droid-core/src/tools/` -- tool name, description, parameter schema. These are included in the system prompt so the LLM knows what tools are available.\n2. **Executors** in `apps/cli/src/tools/` -- the actual implementation that runs when a tool is called. Executors interact with the file system, shell, git, and other system resources.\n\n## Tool categories\n\n| Category | Examples |\n|---|---|\n| File operations | Read, Create, Edit, MultiEdit (file content manipulation) |\n| Search | Grep, Glob (code search and file discovery) |\n| Shell | Execute (run shell commands with timeout and risk assessment) |\n| Git | Git operations through shell commands |\n| Web | WebSearch, FetchUrl (internet access) |\n| Browser | Browser automation via Chrome DevTools |\n| UI | AskUser, TodoWrite, ExitSpecMode (user interaction) |\n| Agent | Task (spawn sub-agents), Skill (invoke skills) |\n\n## Permission model\n\nTools have a risk level system:\n- **Low risk** -- read-only operations (file reads, searches, git status). Auto-approved.\n- **Medium risk** -- file modifications, package installs. May require confirmation.\n- **High risk** -- destructive operations, git push, running untrusted code. Requires explicit approval.\n\n## MCP tools\n\nIn addition to built-in tools, Droid can use tools provided by MCP (Model Context Protocol) servers. See [MCP integration](./mcp-integration.md).\n\n## Key source files\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `packages/droid-core/src/tools/` | Tool interface definitions |\n| `apps/cli/src/tools/tui.ts` | Tool registry for TUI mode |\n| `apps/cli/src/tools/client.ts` | Tool client abstraction |\n| `apps/cli/src/hooks/useToolExecution.ts` | Tool execution hook |\n",
